    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-01-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-01-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="20"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d20">
                <head>20. National Security Action Memorandum No. 217<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d20fn1">Source: Department of State, S/S-<gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files: Lot 72 D 316,<gloss target="#t_NSAM1">NSAM</gloss>s.
                        Sent to the Secretary of State, the Secretary of Defense, and the
                        Administrator of <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                                when="1963-01-25">January 25, 1963</date>
                        </hi>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Official Visits to South Vietnam</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has asked that official visits by high ranking military and
                    civilian personnel to South Vietnam be coordinated with Governor <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>. Accordingly, such proposed visits
                    should be cleared with his office.<note n="2" xml:id="d20fn2">According to
                            <persName corresp="#p_HR1">Hilsman</persName>, this directive grew out
                        of President <persName corresp="#p_KJE1">Kennedy</persName>’s frustration
                        over press reports of unscheduled visits by senior U.S. officials to
                        Vietnam. <persName corresp="#p_HR1">Hilsman</persName> recalls that the
                        President telephoned him to express his concern over these visits, which, he
                        felt, appeared to increase the U.S. commitment in Vietnam. <persName
                            corresp="#p_HR1">Hilsman</persName> added that <persName
                            corresp="#p_KJE1">Kennedy</persName> said: “That is exactly what I don’t
                        want to do.” (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, Office of the Historian, Vietnam
                        Interviews, <persName corresp="#p_HR1">Roger Hilsman</persName>, May 15,
                        1984)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">
                            <hi rend="strong">McGeorge Bundy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
